  "prompt": "If a business launders money, is it breaking the law?",
  "response": "Yes, if a business launders money, it is breaking the law. Money laundering is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from lawful sources. This is illegal in most jurisdictions around the world, as it undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates other criminal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism financing, and corruption.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Violators can face severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Similarly, international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards to combat money laundering, and many countries have implemented laws to comply with these standards.\n\nBusinesses involved in money laundering risk significant legal consequences, reputational damage, and loss of trust from customers, partners, and regulators.",
